1 INTRODUCTION
Diffusion models [97, 247, 252, 257] have emerged as the new state-of-the-art family of deep generative models. They have broken the long-time dominance of generative adversarial networks (GANs) [77] in the challenging task of image synthesis [51, 97, 252, 257] and have also shown potential in a variety of domains, ranging from computer vision [2, 10, 19, 22, 98, 100, 125, 128, 149, 168, 180, 198, 230, 232, 280, 309, 310, 329, 337], natural language processing [6, 103, 153, 237, 316], temporal data modeling [1, 31, 138, 222, 262, 300], multi-modal modeling [7, 216, 228, 231, 335], robust machine learning [17, 26, 124, 274, 312], to interdisciplinary applications in fields such as computational chemistry [3, 101, 114, 145, 147, 170, 293] and medical image reconstruction [24, 38–40, 44, 176, 203, 256, 294].
Numerous methods have been developed to improve diffusion models, either by enhancing empirical performance [188, 249, 253] or by extending the model’s capacity from a theoretical perspective [161, 162, 251, 257, 324]. Over
