7.5 Temporal Data Modeling
7.5.1 Time Series Imputation. Time series data are widely used with many important real-world applications [63, 196, 305, 327]. Nevertheless, time series usually contain missing values for multiple reasons, caused by mechanical or artificial errors [244, 261, 311]. Recent years, imputation methods have been greatly for both deterministic imputation [25, 29, 171] and probabilistic imputation [68], including diffusion-based approaches. Conditional Score-based Diffusion models for Imputation (CSDI) [262] presents a novel time series imputation method that leverages score-based diffusion models. Specifically, for the purpose of exploiting correlations within temporal data, it adopts the form of self-supervised training to optimize diffusion models. Its application in some real-world datasets reveals its superiority over previous methods. Controlled Stochastic Differential Equation (CSDE) [201] proposes a novel probabilistic framework for modeling stochastic dynamics with a neural-controlled stochastic differential equation. Structured State Space Diffusion (SSSD) [1] integrates conditional diffusion models and structured state-space models [86] to particularly capture long-term dependencies in time series. It performs well in both time series imputation and forecasting tasks.

Fig. 15. The procedure of time series imputation with CSDI [262].
7.5.2 Time Series Forecasting. Time series forecasting is the task of forecasting or predicting the future value over a period of time. Neural methods have recently become widely-used for solving the prediction problem with univariate point forecasting methods [195] or univariate probabilistic methods [235]. In the multivariate setting, we also have point forecasting methods [152] as well as probabilistic methods, which explicitly model the data distribution using Gaussian copulas [236], GANs [313], or normalizing flows [222]. TimeGrad [221] presents an autoregressive model for forecasting multivariate probabilistic time series, which samples from the data distribution at each time step through estimating its gradient. It utilizes diffusion probabilistic models, which are closely connected with score matching and energy-based methods. Specifically, it learns gradients by optimizing a variational bound on the data likelihood and transforms white noise into a sample of the distribution of interest through a Markov chain using Langevin sampling [252] during inference time.
7.5.3 Waveform Signal Processing. In electronics, acoustics, and some related fields, the waveform of a signal is denoted by the shape of its graph as a function of time, independent of its time and magnitude scales. WaveGrad [31] introduces a conditional model for waveform generation that estimates gradients of the data density. It receives a Gaussian white noise signal as input and iteratively refines the signal with a gradient-based sampler. WaveGrad naturally trades
Manuscript submitted to ACM

Diffusion Models: A Comprehensive Survey of Methods and Applications

35

inference speed for sample quality by adjusting the number of refinement steps, and make a connection between nonautoregressive and autoregressive models with respect to audio quality. DiffWave [138] presents a versatile and effective diffusion probabilistic model for conditional or unconditional waveform generation. The model is non-autoregressive and is efficiently trained by optimizing a variant of variational bound on the data likelihood. Moreover, it produces high-fidelity audio in different waveform generation tasks, such as class-conditional generation and unconditional generation.
7.6 Robust Learning
Robust learning is a class of defense methods that help learning networks that are robust to adversarial perturbations or noises [17, 190, 206, 274, 285, 312]. While adversarial training [174] is viewed as a standard defense method against adversarial attacks for image classifiers, adversarial purification has shown significant performances as an alternative defense method [312], which purifies attacked images into clean images with a standalone purification model. Given an adversarial example, DiffPure [190] diffuses it with a small amount of noise following a forward diffusion process and then restores the clean image with a reverse generative process. Adaptive Denoising Purification (ADP) [312] demonstrates that an EBM trained with denoising score matching [272] can effectively purify attacked images within just a few steps. It further proposes an effective randomized purification scheme, injecting random noises into images before purification. Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) [17] presents a novel stochastic diffusion-based pre-processing robustification, which aims to be a model-agnostic adversarial defense and yield a high-quality denoised outcome. In addition, some works propose to apply a guided diffusion process for advanced adversarial purification [274, 285].

7.7 Interdisciplinary Applications
7.7.1 Drug Design and Life Science. Graph Neural Networks [90, 288, 307, 333] and corresponding representation learning [91] techniques have achieved great success [15, 264, 287, 297, 304, 336] in many areas, including modeling molecules/proteins in various tasks ranging from property prediction [62, 74] to molecule/protein generation [112, 119, 169, 242], where a molecule is naturally represented by a node-edge graph. On one hand, recent works propose to pre-train GNN/transformer [166, 332] specifically for molecules/proteins with biomedical or physical insights [157, 319], and achieve remarkable results. On the other hand, more works begin to utilize graph-based diffusion models for enhancing molecule or protein generation. Torsional diffusion [114] presents a new diffusion framework that makes operations on the space of torsion angles with a diffusion process on the hyperspace and an extrinsic-to-intrinsic scoring model. GeoDiff [298] demonstrates that Markov chains evolving with equivariant Markov kernels can produce an invariant distribution, and further design blocks for the Markov kernels to preserve the desirable equivariance property. There are also other works incorporate the equivariance property into 3D molecule generation [101] and protein generation [3, 14]. Motivated by the classical force field methods for simulating molecular dynamics, ConfGF [241] directly estimates the gradient fields of the log density of atomic coordinates in molecular conformation generation.

